i## title: My first Linux From Scratch system	/	tilde.team	70
i## date: "2025-03-29"	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i## Introduction	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iIn this blog post, I will refer to Linux From Scratch by	/	tilde.team	70
iwriting "LFS".	/	tilde.team	70
hLinux From Scratch	URL:https://www.linuxfromscratch.org	www.linuxfromscratch.org	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iI heard about LFS by stumbling across a podcast by Brodie	/	tilde.team	70
iRobertson. I've been curious and made me want to build my	/	tilde.team	70
iown Linux system.	/	tilde.team	70
hpodcast	URL:https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TkkKNfYKJJg	www.youtube.com	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
i## What is LFS?	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iIt's a book that explains how to build your own Linux system	/	tilde.team	70
ifrom scratch using a host system. An interesting feature is	/	tilde.team	70
ithat everything is built from source code.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i## My objectives	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iIn reading LFS, I have some very specific goals. I'd like my	/	tilde.team	70
isystem to be able to run my favorite games, i.e. DDNet and	/	tilde.team	70
iQuake I. To do this, I'll need a kernel that can communicate	/	tilde.team	70
iwith my hardware, at least the video, audio and network	/	tilde.team	70
iparts, so that I can access the Internet, etc.	/	tilde.team	70
hDDNet	URL:https://ddnet.org/	ddnet.org	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iI'd also like to have a simple, lightweight desktop	/	tilde.team	70
ienvironment based on the graphics server Xorg.	/	tilde.team	70
hXorg	URL:https://www.x.org/wiki/	www.x.org	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iAnd most important of all, I'd like to be able to boot into	/	tilde.team	70
imy system directly on my computer.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i## Building LFS	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iSo I started reading the book and setting up my system. More	/	tilde.team	70
iprecisely, I chose version 12.2 with systemd (French	/	tilde.team	70
iversion) as init daemon and with Linux version 6.10.5. In	/	tilde.team	70
ithis section, I'm not going to reexplain all the steps in	/	tilde.team	70
ithe book, just highlight the most important ones in my	/	tilde.team	70
iopinion.	/	tilde.team	70
hversion 12.2 with systemd (French version)	URL:https://fr.linuxfromscratch.org/view/lfs-12.2-systemd-fr/	fr.linuxfromscratch.org	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
i### Disk partitioning	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iI chose to make a single 40GiB ext4 partition on my laptop's	/	tilde.team	70
ihard disk. I declared it in my NixOS configuration, with	/	tilde.team	70
ipartitioning handled by the NixOS disko module.	/	tilde.team	70
hNixOS	URL:https://nixos.org	nixos.org	443
hNixOS	URL:https://nixos.org	nixos.org	443
hdisko	URL:https://github.com/nix-community/disko	github.com	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
ilfs = {	/	tilde.team	70
i  name = "LFS";	/	tilde.team	70
i  size = "40G";	/	tilde.team	70
i  content = {	/	tilde.team	70
i    type = "filesystem";	/	tilde.team	70
i    format = "ext4";	/	tilde.team	70
i    mountpoint = "/mnt/lfs";	/	tilde.team	70
i  };	/	tilde.team	70
i};	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i### Compiling the compiler compiling a compiler	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iAn important part of LFS is cross-compiling. The aim is to	/	tilde.team	70
ibuild the tools of the construction chain dedicated to my	/	tilde.team	70
iLFS system. This cross-compilation is "false", i.e. in the	/	tilde.team	70
iend, the hardware of my host system and that of my LFS	/	tilde.team	70
isystem are the same. Only the target system changes.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iHere's a diagram representing the cross-compilation steps,	/	tilde.team	70
iwhere each rectangle represents a compiler containing a	/	tilde.team	70
isource platform to destination platform relationship.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i/lfs_cross-compilation.png	/	tilde.team	70
I/lfs_cross-compilation.png	/~nagi/lfs_cross-compilation.png	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i### Basic softwares and configuration	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iAfter entering my new system (chroot), I was able to	/	tilde.team	70
iestablish a base.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iI installed all the basic tools you'd want on a Linux system	/	tilde.team	70
iand wrote configuration files for the various applications	/	tilde.team	70
iand services (systemd, network, shells, time, language,	/	tilde.team	70
ietc.).	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i### Linux	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iI built Linux by passing the right values to its parameters,	/	tilde.team	70
iso as to be as compatible as possible with my hardware.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iI activated the right drivers to communicate with my network	/	tilde.team	70
icard and audio hardware. By default, I was missing a few	/	tilde.team	70
ifirmwares that needed to be loaded, so I embedded them in	/	tilde.team	70
ithe kernel.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iOnce built and installed on my LFS system, all that's left	/	tilde.team	70
ito do is load Linux.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i### Boot	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iTo be able to boot on my LFS system, I added an entry for	/	tilde.team	70
ithe GRUB managed by my main NixOS system. To do this, I	/	tilde.team	70
irebuilt my NixOS system using os-pober, as shown below.	/	tilde.team	70
hNixOS	URL:https://nixos.org	nixos.org	443
hNixOS	URL:https://nixos.org	nixos.org	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iloader.grub = {	/	tilde.team	70
i  useOSProber = true;	/	tilde.team	70
i};	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i## Beyond LFS	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iNow that I have a basic system that I can boot, the goal is	/	tilde.team	70
ito have a desktop environment before I can play.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iI had to build the entire graphics system X and its	/	tilde.team	70
idependencies, before building the window manager i3, then	/	tilde.team	70
iKDE Plasma 6 and finally Xfce.	/	tilde.team	70
